This error is related to Firebase security rules. The user doesn't have sufficient permissions to read data from the "FutureMK" collection in Firestore. To fix this, you need to adjust your Firestore security rules to allow read access to this collection for authenticated users. 

For example, you could modify the rules to look like this: 

```
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /FutureMK/{document=**} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null; // allow authenticated users to read and write
    }
  }
}
```

Make sure to test your rules thoroughly and only give enough access to authenticated users as needed for your app's functionality.

You can modify your Firestore security rules to allow all users and guests to read data, but only an authenticated admin user to write data. Here's an example of how your rules could be written:

```
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /FutureMK/{document=**} {
      allow read: if true; // allow all users and guests to read
      allow write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == "YOUR_ADMIN_UID"; // allow only authenticated admin user to write
    }
  }
}
```

Replace "YOUR_ADMIN_UID" with the unique ID of your admin user. You can find this ID in the Firebase console under the Authentication tab.

With these rules, any user or guest can read the "FutureMK" collection, but only an authenticated user with the specified admin UID can write to it. Make sure to thoroughly test and adjust these security rules as needed to fit the needs of your app.

This error happens when you try to pass a non-serializable object in the navigation params. In your case, you're trying to pass an image in the `SignUpForMK` navigation. 

The recommended way of passing data between screens is to pass only serializable data types such as strings, numbers, booleans, and objects with primitive values. What you can do is to modify your navigation so that you pass the image URL instead of the entire image object. You can then use the URL to display the image in `SignUpForMK` screen.

Here's an example of how you can modify your navigation:

```
<Pressable
  style={gStyle.FutureMKmoreDetails}
  onPress={() => {
    navigation.navigate('SignUpForMK', { imageUrl: mkData.imageUrl }); // pass imageUrl instead of mkData
  }}
>
```

Note that we're passing only the `imageUrl` property of `mkData` instead of the entire `mkData` object.

Then, in your `SignUpForMK` screen, you can use the `imageUrl` passed in the navigation params to display the image, like this:

```
import { Image } from 'react-native';

// ...

// use the imageUrl to display the image
<Image source={{ uri: route.params.imageUrl }} style={/* your image style */} />
```

This should fix the error and allow you to pass the necessary data between screens.

import { Text, View, Image, Pressable } from 'react-native';
